#Calculation for Volatility

df['Year'] = df['Date'].dt.year
df['Daily Return'] = df['Adj Close'].pct_change() #Daily Returns represents % of changes in stock Market , which can be calculated using Adj Close.
annual_volatility_per_year = df.groupby('Year')['Daily Return'].std() * np.sqrt(252) # number of trading day per year ( excluding weekends and Bank holidays)
volatility_table = annual_volatility_per_year.reset_index()
volatility_table.columns = ['Year', 'Annualized Volatility']
print(volatility_table)
print(f"The Annual Volatility of the studied stock is {annual_volatility_per_year.sum():.2f}")

2. Univariate Analysis¶

The following section will help us visualise how the data bahaves. From left to right : The first graph shows how many times the stock finished at x-axis value Then the time series plot followed by yearly average to see a general trend

In [133]:
# Univariate analysis function

def univariate_analysis(df, selected_column, y_label): 
    column = df[selected_column]

    # Skewness of the distribution
    skew = column.skew()
    print(f'The skewness of the distribution is {skew} for {selected_column}')

    # Kurtosis of the distribution
    kurtosis = column.kurtosis()
    print(f'The kurtosis of the distribution is {kurtosis} for {selected_column}')

    # This creates a subplots with 1 row and 3 columns
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(28, 8))

    # Plotting the histogram
    sns.histplot(df, x=column, ax=axes[0], color='black')
    axes[0].set_xlabel(y_label)
    axes[0].set_title(f'Histogram for {selected_column}',fontweight='bold', loc='center')




    # Line plot
    sns.lineplot(data=df, x='Date', y=column, ax=axes[1], color='black')
    axes[1].set_ylabel(y_label)
    axes[1].set_xlabel('Year')
    axes[1].set_title(f'Time Series Plot for {selected_column}',fontweight='bold', loc='center')


    # Yearly average graph with standard deviation
    df_yearly = df.copy()
    df_yearly['year'] = pd.to_datetime(df['Date']).dt.year
    yearly_stats = df_yearly.groupby('year')[selected_column].agg(['mean', 'std']).reset_index()
    years = yearly_stats['year']
    mean_values = yearly_stats['mean']
    std_values = yearly_stats['std']
    axes[2].plot(years, mean_values, label='Yearly Average', color='black')
    axes[2].fill_between(years, mean_values - std_values, mean_values + std_values, alpha=0.3, label='Standard Deviation', color='black')
    axes[2].set_title(f'Yearly Average with Standard Deviation for {selected_column}',fontweight='bold', loc='center')
    axes[2].set_xlabel('Year')
    axes[2].set_ylabel(y_label)
    axes[2].legend()
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

# Plot Time Series Data
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.plot(df['Date'], df['Close'], label='Time Series')
plt.title('Time Series Data')
plt.xlabel('Date')
plt.ylabel('Closing Price')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

#Autocorrelation Plot
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))

# ACF Plot
plt.subplot(121)
ax=plt.gca()
plot_acf(df['Close'], ax, lags=100)
plt.title('Autocorrelation Function')

# PACF Plot
plt.subplot(122)
ax=plt.gca()
plot_pacf(df['Close'], ax, lags=100) # lags represents the number of previous values looked at in order to compare with the value at time t.
plt.title('Partial Autocorrelation Function')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Seasonality Plot
decomposition_timeSeries = seasonal_decompose(df['Close'], model='additive', period=12)
# Plotting
decomposition_timeSeries.plot()
ax.xaxis.set_major_formatter(mdates.DateFormatter('%Y'))
plt.show()

Saving the file in HTML is way to not have to re run the code and see several outputs.This is to facilitate the code consultation while marking The code below has been extracted online and is only use for file conversion as saving as HTML built in function was causing trouble.

import nbformat
from nbconvert import HTMLExporter

# Load the notebook
with open('/Users/aliabouyahia/Desktop/Code_Final_Project_1737703/EDA Python/EDA_Daily_Data.ipynb','r') as f:
    notebook_content = nbformat.read(f, as_version=4)

# Convert to HTML
html_exporter = HTMLExporter()
html_content, resources = html_exporter.from_notebook_node(notebook_content)

# Write to an HTML file
with open('EDA_Daily_Data_AMZN.html', 'w') as f:
    f.write(html_content)
